On this ‘sequacitas et coitio' in the case of Aristode, cp. the beginning of Campanella's treatise ‘Philosophia sensibus demonstrata,' &c (published at Naples in 1591), where we find him complaining: ‘Et si quando quaestionem sensatae rei tractant, non quod in re est vident3 sed quod in verbis Aristotelis scripturn inveniunt, et ex eis arguunt, et ex eis re- spondent, et si ipsa rei natura sensibus contrariam Aristoteli se offerat nolentibus et invitis, dicunt Aristotelem non errasse? ‘Hinc fugientes rerum scientias, conterunt inter se tempus de subjectis scientiarum apud Aristotelem . . . . lta quod nunquam (Mehercule) vidi unum ex eis res inspicere, ad campos tendere, maria, et montes, utres spectent, nec in propriis domibus, sed tanturn a libris Aristotelis, et superbis stant semper.¹ PP· ²2 3·

Many similar illustrations will be found among the passages quoted from the opponents oi the Aristotelian philosophy in the Introduction, § re.

⁹ Bacon’s impatience with the ever-recurrlng appeal to authority has, of course, here betrayed him into exaggeration. Consent, however danger· nus it may be to accept it as an ultimate argument, is, there can be no doubt, rather a presumption in favour of an opinion than against it. ‘Securus judicat orbis terrarum’ is an over-strained axiom, but, oi the two exaggerations, it is nearer the truth than the ‘Pessimum omnium est augurium’ &c of Bacon.
